'''Aron Brand-Auraban''' (21 February 1910 - 22 April 1977), born in [[Ozorków]], [[Poland]], was an [[Israeli Jews|Israel]]i pediatric cardiologist. He served as chairman of the [[Israel Medical Association]] in [[Jerusalem]], [[Israel]], and founded the [[Jerusalem Academy of Medicine]].<ref name="books.google.com">[http://books.google.com/books?id=yqXXD_74yAEC&pg=PA68&lpg=PA68&dq=eisenberg+streets+of+jerusalem+brand&source=bl&ots=oqIWfGuVqV&sig=HTJI25_xu9NlPSnGLAz6vnkWHKc&hl=en&ei=RIvVSonJDIX54AaqydDWDA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CBIQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=&f=false ''The Streets of Jerusalem: Who, what, why'', Ronald L. Eisenberg]</ref>

==Biography==
Aron Brand grew up in [[Koło]], where he attended [[heder]] and the Jewish gymnasium. His father, Natan, was a grain merchant and miller. In 1925, his father, a fervent [[Zionism|Zionist]], sent him to [[British Mandate of Palestine|Palestine]] to study at [[Gymnasia Herzliya]] in [[Tel Aviv]].<ref name="APF News 1970, p.12">APF News, American Physicians Fellowship Inc. for the Israel Medical Association, Prof. Brand-Auraban of Jerusalem: A Saga of the Eternal Jew, March 1970, p.12</ref> In 1928, he studied philosophy and [[Jewish studies]] in Berlin.<ref name="who">Who's who in Israel and in the work for Israel abroad. Bronfman & Cohen Publications, 1973. p.75</ref> He studied simultaneously at the University of Berlin and the [[Hochschule fuer die Wissenschaft des Judentums]].<ref name="APF News 1970, p.12"/> 

In 1935, Brand completed his doctoral thesis in the [[Humboldt University of Berlin|Friedrich-Wilhelms university of Berlin]].

In the summer of 1939, Brand returned to Poland and married Esther Malka (Mala) née [[Auerbach (Jewish family)|Aurbach]], of [[Przedecz]]. By a stroke of luck, they left Poland one day before the [[Nazis]] invaded. At the time, Brand was a teacher at the Ma'aleh School in Jerusalem. The couple had three sons, Avraham, [[Natan Brand|Natan]] and Haim.

==Medical career==
In 1955, Brand founded the Jerusalem Academy of Medicine. From 1964 until his death, he headed the Pediatric Department of [[Bikur Cholim Hospital]] in Jerusalem. He was the founder of the Israel Institute for Medical History. In 1969-1970, he was a visiting associate professor of pediatrics at [[Harvard College]] in [[Boston, Massachusetts]].<ref>E. Seidler. Judische Kinderarzte 1933-1945: Entrechtet, geflohen, ermordet, Jewish Pediatricians, Victims of Persecution 1933-1945. Karger Publishers, 2007. p.139-140</ref>

Brand published numerous articles on medicine, philosophy, literature and art, and organized hundreds of lectures and workshops open to the general public on health-related issues. In 1976, he was awarded the [[Henrietta Szold]] Prize for his contribution to public health.<ref>''Prof. Aron Brand-Auraban Memorial Volume'' edited by Haim Toren, Rubin Mass, Jerusalem, 1978</ref>

==Commemoration==
Rehov Aron Brand, a street in the [[Har Nof]] neighborhood of Jerusalem, is named after him.<ref name="books.google.com"/>

